  "prompt": "What is the difference between a grade of A+ and an A at the University of Illinois?",
  "response": "At the University of Illinois, the grading scale typically designates an A as a 4.0 grade point average (GPA) and an A+ as a 4.0 GPA as well. Essentially, both grades represent the highest level of achievement in a course. However, some institutions may recognize an A+ as a cut above an A, sometimes leading to differences in how it is viewed in certain contexts, such as class rankings or GPA calculations. \n\nIt's important to note that specific grading policies can vary by department or program, so students are encouraged to check their particular program's guidelines for any nuances between these grades.",
